class Solution {
public:
    int searchInsert(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int mid = 0;
        int s = 0,e = n-1;
        while(s<=e){
            mid = s+(e-s)/2;
            if(nums[mid]==target){
                return mid;
            }
            else if(nums[mid]<target){
                s = mid+1;
            }
            else{
                e = mid-1;
            }
        }
        if(nums[mid]<target) return mid+1;
        else return mid;
    }
};

"idea:
This solution uses the Binary Search algorithm to efficiently find the target or its correct insertion position in a sorted array.
We initialize two pointers, s (start) and e (end), to search within the array range.
In every iteration, the middle index mid is calculated using s + (e - s) / 2 to avoid integer overflow.
If nums[mid] equals the target, the index is returned immediately.
If the target is greater than nums[mid], the search moves to the right half by updating s = mid + 1; otherwise, it searches the left half using e = mid - 1.
The loop continues until the search space becomes invalid (s > e).
After the loop, mid helps determine the correct insertion index: if nums[mid] < target, insert at mid + 1; otherwise, insert at mid.
"

#Time Complexity : O(log n)                    Space Complexity: O(1)
